# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: yeast
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:yeast/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:yeast/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:yeast/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:yeast/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:yeast/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:yeast/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:yeast/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:yeast/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:yeast/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:yeast/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:yeast/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:yeast/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:yeast/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:yeast/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:yeast/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:yeast/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:yeast/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:yeast/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:yeast/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:yeast/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:yeast/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:yeast/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:yeast/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:yeast/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:yeast/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:yeast/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:yeast/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:yeast/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:yeast/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:yeast/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:yeast/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:yeast/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:yeast/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:yeast/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:yeast/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:yeast/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:yeast/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:yeast/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:yeast/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:yeast/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:yeast/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:yeast/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:yeast/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:yeast/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:yeast/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:yeast/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:yeast/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:yeast/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:yeast/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:yeast/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:yeast/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:yeast/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:yeast/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:yeast/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:yeast/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:yeast/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:yeast/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:yeast/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:yeast/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:yeast/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] All acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other good sources are fresh apple cider and unpasteurized beer that has not been filter sterilized.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] In these liquids, they grow as a surface film due to their aerobic nature and active motility.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Fruit flies or vinegar eels are considered common vectors in the propagation of acetic acid bacteria.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] The growth of *Acetobacter* in wine can be suppressed through effective sanitation, by complete exclusion of air from wine in storage, and by the use of moderate amounts of sulfur dioxide in the wine as a preservative.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Vinegar is produced when acetic acid bacteria act on alcoholic beverages such as wine.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Specific oxidation reactions occur through oxidative fermentation, which creates vinegar as a byproduct.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] In the biotechnological industry, these bacteria's oxidation mechanism is exploited to produce a number of compounds such as l-ascorbic acid, dihydroxyacetone, gluconic acid, and cellulose.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Besides food industry, some acetic acid bacteria are used as biocatalysts for the industrial production of compounds.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are used as the important biocatalysts for the development of eco-friendly fermentation processes as an alternative to the chemical synthesis.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Some genera, such as *Acetobacter*, can oxidize ethanol to carbon dioxide and water using Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other genera, such as *Gluconobacter*, do not oxidize ethanol, as they do not have a full set of Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] As these bacteria produce acid, they are usually acid-tolerant, growing well below pH 5.0, although the pH optimum for growth is 5.4-6.3.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid-bacteria] *Acetobacter xylinum* is able to synthesize cellulose, something normally done only by plants.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:yeast/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:yeast/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:yeast/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:yeast/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:yeast/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:yeast/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:yeast/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:yeast/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:yeast/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:yeast/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:yeast/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:yeast/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:yeast/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:yeast/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:yeast/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:yeast/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:yeast/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:yeast/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:yeast/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:yeast/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:yeast/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:yeast/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:yeast/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:yeast/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:yeast/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:yeast/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:yeast/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:yeast/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:yeast/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:yeast/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:yeast/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:yeast/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:yeast/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:yeast/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:yeast/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:yeast/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:yeast/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:yeast/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:yeast/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:yeast/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:yeast/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:yeast/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:yeast/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:yeast/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:yeast/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:yeast/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:yeast/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:yeast/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:yeast/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:yeast/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:yeast/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:yeast/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:yeast/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:yeast/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:yeast/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:yeast/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:yeast/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:yeast/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:yeast/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:yeast/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:yeast/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:yeast/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:yeast/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:yeast/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:yeast/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:yeast/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:yeast/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:yeast/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:yeast/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:yeast/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:yeast/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:yeast/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:yeast/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:yeast/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:yeast/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:yeast/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:yeast/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:yeast/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:yeast/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:yeast/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:yeast/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:yeast/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:yeast/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:yeast/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:yeast/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:yeast/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:yeast/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:yeast/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:yeast/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:yeast/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:yeast/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:yeast/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:yeast/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:yeast/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:yeast/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:yeast/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:yeast/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:yeast/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:yeast/yeast] A **yeast** is any species of fungus that grows primarily in a unicellular form and reproduces via budding or fission.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts are eukaryotic microorganisms that originated hundreds of millions of years ago, with at least 1,500 species currently recognized.
[src:yeast/yeast] They constitute about 1% of all described fungal species.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some yeast species have the ability to develop multicellular characteristics by forming strings of connected budding cells known as pseudohyphae or false hyphae, or quickly evolve into a multicellular cluster with specialised cell organelle functions.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast sizes vary greatly, depending on species and environment, typically measuring 3–4 μm in diameter, although some yeasts can grow to 40 μm in size.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most yeasts reproduce asexually by mitosis, and many do so by the asymmetric division process known as budding.
[src:yeast/yeast] With their single-celled growth habit, yeasts can be contrasted with molds, which grow hyphae.
[src:yeast/yeast] Fungal species that can take both forms (depending on temperature or other conditions) are called dimorphic fungi.
[src:yeast/yeast] The yeast species *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* converts carbohydrates to carbon dioxide and alcohols through the process of fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] The products of this reaction have been used in baking and the production of alcoholic beverages for thousands of years.
[src:yeast/yeast] *S. cerevisiae* is also an important model organism in modern cell biology research, and is one of the most thoroughly studied eukaryotic microorganisms.
[src:yeast/yeast] Researchers have cultured it in order to understand the biology of the eukaryotic cell and ultimately human biology in great detail.
[src:yeast/yeast] Other species of yeasts, such as *Candida albicans*, are opportunistic pathogens and can cause infections in humans.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts have recently been used to generate electricity in microbial fuel cells and to produce ethanol for the biofuel industry.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts do not form a single taxonomic or phylogenetic grouping.
[src:yeast/yeast] The term "yeast" is often taken as a synonym for *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, but the phylogenetic diversity of yeasts is shown by their placement in two separate phyla: the Ascomycota and the Basidiomycota.
[src:yeast/yeast] The budding yeasts, or "true yeasts", are classified in the order Saccharomycetales, within the phylum Ascomycota.
[src:yeast/yeast] The word *yeast* comes from Old English *gist, gyst*, and from the Indo-European root **yes-*, meaning "boil", "foam", or "bubble".
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast microbes are probably one of the earliest domesticated organisms.
[src:yeast/yeast] Archaeologists digging in Egyptian ruins found early grinding stones and baking chambers for yeast-raised bread, as well as drawings of 4,000-year-old bakeries and breweries.
[src:yeast/yeast] In 1680, Dutch naturalist Anton van Leeuwenhoek first microscopically observed yeast, but at the time did not consider them to be living organisms, but rather globular structures as researchers were doubtful whether yeasts were algae or fungi.
[src:yeast/yeast] Theodor Schwann recognized them as fungi in 1837.
[src:yeast/yeast] In 1857, French microbiologist Louis Pasteur showed that by bubbling oxygen into the yeast broth, cell growth could be increased, but fermentation was inhibited – an observation later called the "Pasteur effect".
[src:yeast/yeast] In the paper "*Mémoire sur la fermentation alcoolique,*" Pasteur proved that alcoholic fermentation was conducted by living yeasts and not by a chemical catalyst.
[src:yeast/yeast] By the late 18th century two yeast strains used in brewing had been identified: *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* (top-fermenting yeast) and *S. pastorianus* (bottom-fermenting yeast).
[src:yeast/yeast] *S. cerevisiae* has been sold commercially by the Dutch for bread-making since 1780; while, around 1800, the Germans started producing *S. cerevisiae* in the form of cream.
[src:yeast/yeast] In 1825, a method was developed to remove the liquid so the yeast could be prepared as solid blocks.
[src:yeast/yeast] The industrial production of yeast blocks was enhanced by the introduction of the filter press in 1867.
[src:yeast/yeast] In 1872, Baron Max de Springer developed a manufacturing process to create granulated yeast from beetroot molasses, a technique that was used until the first World War.
[src:yeast/yeast] In the United States, naturally occurring airborne yeasts were used almost exclusively until commercial yeast was marketed at the Centennial Exposition in 1876 in Philadelphia, where Charles L.
[src:yeast/yeast] Fleischmann exhibited the product and a process to use it, as well as serving the resultant baked bread.
[src:yeast/yeast] The mechanical refrigerator (first patented in the 1850s in Europe) liberated brewers and winemakers from seasonal constraints for the first time and allowed them to exit cellars and other earthen environments.
[src:yeast/yeast] For John Molson, who made his livelihood in Montreal prior to the development of the refrigerator, the brewing season lasted from September through to May.
[src:yeast/yeast] The same seasonal restrictions formerly governed the distiller's art.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts are chemoorganotrophs, as they use organic compounds as a source of energy and do not require sunlight to grow.
[src:yeast/yeast] Carbon is obtained mostly from hexose sugars, such as glucose and fructose, or disaccharides such as sucrose and maltose.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some species can metabolize pentose sugars such as ribose, alcohols, and organic acids.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast species either require oxygen for aerobic cellular respiration (obligate aerobes) or are anaerobic, but also have aerobic methods of energy production (facultative anaerobes).
[src:yeast/yeast] Unlike bacteria, no known yeast species grow only anaerobically (obligate anaerobes).
[src:yeast/yeast] Most yeasts grow best in a neutral or slightly acidic pH environment.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts vary in regard to the temperature range in which they grow best.
[src:yeast/yeast] For example, *Leucosporidium frigidum* grows at −2 to 20 °C (28 to 68 °F), *Saccharomyces telluris* at 5 to 35 °C (41 to 95 °F), and *Candida slooffi* at 28 to 45 °C (82 to 113 °F).
[src:yeast/yeast] The cells can survive freezing under certain conditions, with viability decreasing over time.
[src:yeast/yeast] In general, yeasts are grown in the laboratory on solid growth media or in liquid broths.
[src:yeast/yeast] Common media used for the cultivation of yeasts include potato dextrose agar or potato dextrose broth, Wallerstein Laboratories nutrient agar, yeast peptone dextrose agar, and yeast mould agar or broth.
[src:yeast/yeast] Home brewers who cultivate yeast frequently use dried malt extract and agar as a solid growth medium.
[src:yeast/yeast] The fungicide cycloheximide is sometimes added to yeast growth media to inhibit the growth of *Saccharomyces* yeasts and select for wild/indigenous yeast species.
[src:yeast/yeast] The appearance of a white, thready yeast, commonly known as kahm yeast, is often a byproduct of the lactofermentation (or pickling) of certain vegetables.
[src:yeast/yeast] It is usually the result of exposure to air.
[src:yeast/yeast] Although harmless, it can give pickled vegetables a bad flavor and must be removed regularly during fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts are very common in the environment, and are often isolated from sugar-rich materials.
[src:yeast/yeast] Examples include naturally occurring yeasts on the skins of fruits and berries (such as grapes, apples, or peaches), and exudates from plants (such as plant saps or cacti).
[src:yeast/yeast] Some yeasts are found in association with soil and insects.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts from the soil and from the skins of fruits and berries have been shown to dominate fungal succession during fruit decay.
[src:yeast/yeast] The ecological function and biodiversity of yeasts are relatively unknown compared to those of other microorganisms.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts, including *Candida albicans*, *Rhodotorula rubra*, *Torulopsis* and *Trichosporon cutaneum*, have been found living in between people's toes as part of their skin flora.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts are also present in the gut flora of mammals and some insects and even deep-sea environments host an array of yeasts.
[src:yeast/yeast] An Indian study of seven bee species and nine plant species found 45 species from 16 genera colonize the nectaries of flowers and honey stomachs of bees.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most were members of the genus *Candida*; the most common species in honey stomachs was *Dekkera intermedia* and in flower nectaries, *Candida blankii*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast colonising nectaries of the stinking hellebore have been found to raise the temperature of the flower, which may aid in attracting pollinators by increasing the evaporation of volatile organic compounds.
[src:yeast/yeast] A black yeast has been recorded as a partner in a complex relationship between ants, their mutualistic fungus, a fungal parasite of the fungus and a bacterium that kills the parasite.
[src:yeast/yeast] The yeast has a negative effect on the bacteria that normally produce antibiotics to kill the parasite, so may affect the ants' health by allowing the parasite to spread.
[src:yeast/yeast] A different yeast species is grown by fungus-growing ants of the genus *Cyphomyrmex*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Certain strains of some species of yeasts produce proteins called yeast killer toxins that allow them to eliminate competing strains.
[src:yeast/yeast] (See main article on killer yeast.) This can cause problems for winemaking but could potentially also be used to advantage by using killer toxin-producing strains to make the wine.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast killer toxins may also have medical applications in treating yeast infections (see "Pathogenic yeasts" section below).
[src:yeast/yeast] Marine yeasts, defined as the yeasts that are isolated from marine environments, are able to grow better on a medium prepared using seawater rather than freshwater.
[src:yeast/yeast] The first marine yeasts were isolated by Bernhard Fischer in 1894 from the Atlantic Ocean, and those were identified as *Torula* sp. and *Mycoderma* sp.
[src:yeast/yeast] Following this discovery, various other marine yeasts have been isolated from around the world from different sources, including seawater, seaweeds, marine fish and mammals.
[src:yeast/yeast] Among these isolates, some marine yeasts originated from terrestrial habitats (grouped as facultative marine yeast), which were brought to and survived in marine environments.
[src:yeast/yeast] The other marine yeasts were grouped as obligate or indigenous marine yeasts, which are confined to marine habitats.
[src:yeast/yeast] However, no sufficient evidence has been found to explain the indispensability of seawater for obligate marine yeasts.
[src:yeast/yeast] Marine yeast was successfully used to produce bioethanol using seawater-based media which will potentially reduce the water footprint of bioethanol.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts, like all fungi, may have asexual and sexual reproductive cycles.
[src:yeast/yeast] The most common mode of vegetative growth in yeast is asexual reproduction by budding, where a small bud (also known as a bleb or daughter cell) is formed on the parent cell.
[src:yeast/yeast] The nucleus of the parent cell splits, producing a daughter nucleus that migrates into the daughter cell.
[src:yeast/yeast] The bud then continues to grow until it separates from the parent cell, forming a new cell.
[src:yeast/yeast] The daughter cell produced during the budding process is generally smaller than the mother cell.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some yeasts, including *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, reproduce by fission instead of budding, and thereby creating two identically sized daughter cells.
[src:yeast/yeast] The haploid fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* is a facultative sexual microorganism that can undergo mating when nutrients are limited.
[src:yeast/yeast] Exposure of *S. pombe* to hydrogen peroxide, an agent that causes oxidative stress leading to oxidative DNA damage, strongly induces mating and the formation of meiotic spores.
[src:yeast/yeast] The budding yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* reproduces by mitosis as diploid cells when nutrients are abundant, but when starved, this yeast undergoes meiosis to form haploid spores.
[src:yeast/yeast] Haploid cells may then reproduce asexually by mitosis.
[src:yeast/yeast] Katz Ezov et al. presented evidence that in natural *S. cerevisiae* populations clonal reproduction and selfing (in the form of intratetrad mating) predominate.
[src:yeast/yeast] In nature, the mating of haploid cells to form diploid cells is most often between members of the same clonal population and out-crossing is uncommon.
[src:yeast/yeast] Analysis of the ancestry of natural *S. cerevisiae* strains led to the conclusion that out-crossing occurs only about once every 50,000 cell divisions.
[src:yeast/yeast] These observations suggest that the possible long-term benefits of outcrossing (e.g. generation of diversity) are likely to be insufficient for generally maintaining sex from one generation to the next.
[src:yeast/yeast] Rather, a short-term benefit, such as recombinational repair during meiosis, may be the key to the maintenance of sex in *S. cerevisiae*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some pucciniomycete yeasts, in particular species of *Sporidiobolus* and *Sporobolomyces*, produce aerially dispersed, asexual ballistoconidia.
[src:yeast/yeast] The useful physiological properties of yeast have led to their use in the field of biotechnology.
[src:yeast/yeast] Fermentation of sugars by yeast is the oldest and largest application of this technology.
[src:yeast/yeast] Many types of yeasts are used for making many foods: baker's yeast in bread production, brewer's yeast in beer fermentation, and yeast in wine fermentation and for xylitol production.
[src:yeast/yeast] So-called red rice yeast is actually a mold, *Monascus purpureus*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts include some of the most widely used model organisms for genetics and cell biology.
[src:yeast/yeast] Alcoholic beverages are defined as beverages that contain ethanol (C2H5OH).
[src:yeast/yeast] This ethanol is almost always produced by fermentation – the metabolism of carbohydrates by certain species of yeasts under anaerobic or low-oxygen conditions.
[src:yeast/yeast] Beverages such as mead, wine, beer, or distilled spirits all use yeast at some stage of their production.
[src:yeast/yeast] A distilled beverage is a beverage containing ethanol that has been purified by distillation.
[src:yeast/yeast] Carbohydrate-containing plant material is fermented by yeast, producing a dilute solution of ethanol in the process.
[src:yeast/yeast] Spirits such as whiskey and rum are prepared by distilling these dilute solutions of ethanol.
[src:yeast/yeast] Components other than ethanol are collected in the condensate, including water, esters, and other alcohols, which (in addition to that provided by the oak in which it may be aged) account for the flavour of the beverage.
[src:yeast/yeast] Brewing yeasts may be classed as "top-cropping" (or "top-fermenting") and "bottom-cropping" (or "bottom-fermenting").
[src:yeast/yeast] Top-cropping yeasts are so called because they form a foam at the top of the wort during fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] An example of a top-cropping yeast is *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, sometimes called an "ale yeast".
[src:yeast/yeast] Bottom-cropping yeasts are typically used to produce lager-type beers, though they can also produce ale-type beers.
[src:yeast/yeast] These yeasts ferment well at low temperatures.
[src:yeast/yeast] An example of bottom-cropping yeast is *Saccharomyces pastorianus*, formerly known as *S. carlsbergensis*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Decades ago, taxonomists reclassified *S. carlsbergensis* (uvarum) as a member of *S. cerevisiae*, noting that the only distinct difference between the two is metabolic.
[src:yeast/yeast] Lager strains of *Saccharomyces* secrete an enzyme called melibiase, allowing them to hydrolyse melibiose, a disaccharide, into more fermentable monosaccharides.
[src:yeast/yeast] Top- and bottom-cropping and cold- and warm-fermenting distinctions are largely generalizations used by laypersons to communicate to the general public.
[src:yeast/yeast] The most common top-cropping brewer's yeast, *S. cerevisiae*, is the same species as the common baking yeast.
[src:yeast/yeast] Brewer's yeast is also very rich in essential minerals and the B vitamins (except B12), a feature exploited in food products made from leftover (by-product) yeast from brewing.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast is used in winemaking, where it converts the sugars present (glucose and fructose) in grape juice (must) into ethanol.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast is normally already present on grape skins.
[src:yeast/yeast] Fermentation can be done with this endogenous "wild yeast", but this procedure gives unpredictable results, which depend upon the exact types of yeast species present.
[src:yeast/yeast] For this reason, a pure yeast culture is usually added to the must; this yeast quickly dominates the fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] The wild yeasts are repressed, which ensures a reliable and predictable fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most added wine yeasts are strains of *S. cerevisiae*, though not all strains of the species are suitable.
[src:yeast/yeast] Different *S. cerevisiae* yeast strains have differing physiological and fermentative properties, therefore the actual strain of yeast selected can have a direct impact on the finished wine.
[src:yeast/yeast] Significant research has been undertaken into the development of novel wine yeast strains that produce atypical flavour profiles or increased complexity in wines.
[src:yeast/yeast] The growth of some yeasts, such as *Zygosaccharomyces* and *Brettanomyces*, in wine can result in wine faults and subsequent spoilage.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Brettanomyces* produces an array of metabolites when growing in wine, some of which are volatile phenolic compounds.
[src:yeast/yeast] Together, these compounds are often referred to as "*Brettanomyces* character", and are often described as "antiseptic" or "barnyard" type aromas.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Brettanomyces* is a significant contributor to wine faults within the wine industry.
[src:yeast/yeast] Researchers from the University of British Columbia, Canada, have found a new strain of yeast that has reduced amines.
[src:yeast/yeast] The amines in red wine and Chardonnay produce off-flavors and cause headaches and hypertension in some people.
[src:yeast/yeast] About 30% of people are sensitive to biogenic amines, such as histamines.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast, most commonly *S. cerevisiae*, is used in baking as a leavening agent, converting the fermentable sugars present in dough into carbon dioxide.
[src:yeast/yeast] This causes the dough to expand or rise as gas forms pockets or bubbles.
[src:yeast/yeast] When the dough is baked, the yeast dies and the air pockets "set", giving the baked product a soft and spongy texture.
[src:yeast/yeast] The use of potatoes, water from potato boiling, eggs, or sugar in a bread dough accelerates the growth of yeast.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most yeasts used in baking are of the same species common in alcoholic fermentation.
[src:yeast/yeast] In addition, *Saccharomyces exiguus* (also known as *S. minor*), a wild yeast found on plants, fruits, and grains, is occasionally used for baking.
[src:yeast/yeast] In breadmaking, the yeast initially respires aerobically, producing carbon dioxide and water.
[src:yeast/yeast] When the oxygen is depleted, fermentation begins, producing ethanol as a waste product; however, this evaporates during baking.
[src:yeast/yeast] It is not known when yeast was first used to bake bread.
[src:yeast/yeast] The first records that show this use came from Ancient Egypt.
[src:yeast/yeast] Researchers speculate a mixture of flour meal and water was left longer than usual on a warm day and the yeasts that occur in natural contaminants of the flour caused it to ferment before baking.
[src:yeast/yeast] The resulting bread would have been lighter and tastier than the normal flat, hard cake.
[src:yeast/yeast] Today, there are several retailers of baker's yeast; one of the earlier developments in North America is Fleischmann's Yeast, in 1868.
[src:yeast/yeast] During World War II, Fleischmann's developed a granulated active dry yeast which did not require refrigeration, had a longer shelf life than fresh yeast, and rose twice as fast.
[src:yeast/yeast] Baker's yeast is also sold as a fresh yeast compressed into a square "cake".
[src:yeast/yeast] This form perishes quickly, so must be used soon after production.
[src:yeast/yeast] A weak solution of water and sugar can be used to determine whether yeast is expired.
[src:yeast/yeast] In the solution, active yeast will foam and bubble as it ferments the sugar into ethanol and carbon dioxide.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some recipes refer to this as proofing the yeast, as it "proves" (tests) the viability of the yeast before the other ingredients are added.
[src:yeast/yeast] When a sourdough starter is used, flour and water are added instead of sugar; this is referred to as proofing the sponge.
[src:yeast/yeast] When yeast is used for making bread, it is mixed with flour, salt, and warm water or milk.
[src:yeast/yeast] The dough is kneaded until it is smooth, and then left to rise, sometimes until it has doubled in size.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some bread doughs are knocked back after one rising and left to rise again (this is called dough proofing) and then baked.
[src:yeast/yeast] A longer rising time gives a better flavor, but the yeast can fail to raise the bread in the final stages if it is left for too long initially.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some yeasts can find potential application in the field of bioremediation.
[src:yeast/yeast] One such yeast, *Yarrowia lipolytica*, is known to degrade palm oil mill effluent, TNT (an explosive material), and other hydrocarbons, such as alkanes, fatty acids, fats and oils.
[src:yeast/yeast] It can also tolerate high concentrations of salt and heavy metals, and is being investigated for its potential as a heavy metal biosorbent.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* has potential to bioremediate toxic pollutants like arsenic from industrial effluent.
[src:yeast/yeast] Bronze statues are known to be degraded by certain species of yeast.
[src:yeast/yeast] Different yeasts from Brazilian gold mines bioaccumulate free and complexed silver ions.
[src:yeast/yeast] The ability of yeast to convert sugar into ethanol has been harnessed by the biotechnology industry to produce ethanol fuel.
[src:yeast/yeast] The process starts by milling a feedstock, such as sugar cane, field corn, or other cereal grains, and then adding dilute sulfuric acid, or fungal alpha amylase enzymes, to break down the starches into complex sugars.
[src:yeast/yeast] A glucoamylase is then added to break the complex sugars down into simple sugars.
[src:yeast/yeast] After this, yeasts are added to convert the simple sugars to ethanol, which is then distilled off to obtain ethanol up to 96% in purity.
[src:yeast/yeast] A number of sweet carbonated beverages can be produced by the same methods as beer, except the fermentation is stopped sooner, producing carbon dioxide, but only trace amounts of alcohol, leaving a significant amount of residual sugar in the drink.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast is used as an ingredient in foods for its umami flavor, in much of the same way that monosodium glutamate (MSG) is used and, like MSG, yeast often contains free glutamic acid.
[src:yeast/yeast] Both types of yeast foods above are rich in B-complex vitamins (besides vitamin B12 unless fortified), making them an attractive nutritional supplement to vegans.
[src:yeast/yeast] The same vitamins are also found in some yeast-fermented products mentioned above, such as kvass.
[src:yeast/yeast] Nutritional yeast in particular is naturally low in fat and sodium and a source of protein and vitamins as well as other minerals and cofactors required for growth.
[src:yeast/yeast] Many brands of nutritional yeast and yeast extract spreads, though not all, are fortified with vitamin B12, which is produced separately by bacteria.
[src:yeast/yeast] In 1920, the Fleischmann Yeast Company began to promote yeast cakes in a "Yeast for Health" campaign.
[src:yeast/yeast] They initially emphasized yeast as a source of vitamins, good for skin and digestion.
[src:yeast/yeast] Their later advertising claimed a much broader range of health benefits, and was censured as misleading by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:yeast/yeast] The fad for yeast cakes lasted until the late 1930s.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast cell walls are used as a source of dietary fiber.
[src:yeast/yeast] Specifically, the glucan part is marketed as "yeast β-glucan" and the mannan part is further processed into mannan-oligosaccharide (MOS).
[src:yeast/yeast] Some probiotic supplements use the yeast *S. boulardii* to maintain and restore the natural flora in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast is often used by aquarium hobbyists to generate carbon dioxide (CO2) to nourish plants in planted aquaria.
[src:yeast/yeast] CO2 levels from yeast are more difficult to regulate than those from pressurized CO2 systems.
[src:yeast/yeast] However, the low cost of yeast makes it a widely used alternative.
[src:yeast/yeast] Also, yeasts are easily manipulated and cultured in the laboratory, which has allowed for the development of powerful standard techniques, such as yeast two-hybrid, synthetic genetic array analysis, and tetrad analysis.
[src:yeast/yeast] Many proteins important in human biology were first discovered by studying their homologues in yeast; these proteins include cell cycle proteins, signaling proteins, and protein-processing enzymes.
[src:yeast/yeast] On 24 April 1996, *S. cerevisiae* was announced to be the first eukaryote to have its genome, consisting of 12 million base pairs, fully sequenced as part of the Genome Project.
[src:yeast/yeast] At the time, it was the most complex organism to have its full genome sequenced, and the work of seven years and the involvement of more than 100 laboratories to accomplish.
[src:yeast/yeast] The second yeast species to have its genome sequenced was *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, which was completed in 2002.
[src:yeast/yeast] It was the sixth eukaryotic genome sequenced and consists of 13.8 million base pairs.
[src:yeast/yeast] As of 2014, over 50 yeast species have had their genomes sequenced and published.
[src:yeast/yeast] Genomic and functional gene annotation of the two major yeast models can be accessed via their respective model organism databases: SGD and PomBase.
[src:yeast/yeast] Various yeast species have been genetically engineered to efficiently produce various drugs, a technique called metabolic engineering.
[src:yeast/yeast] *S. cerevisiae* is easy to genetically engineer; its physiology, metabolism and genetics are well known, and it is amenable for use in harsh industrial conditions.
[src:yeast/yeast] A wide variety of chemical in different classes can be produced by engineered yeast, including phenolics, isoprenoids, alkaloids, and polyketides.
[src:yeast/yeast] About 20% of biopharmaceuticals are produced in *S. cerevisiae*, including insulin, vaccines for hepatitis, and human serum albumin.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some species of yeast are opportunistic pathogens that can cause infection in people with compromised immune systems.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Cryptococcus neoformans* and *Cryptococcus gattii* are significant pathogens of immunocompromised people.
[src:yeast/yeast] They are the species primarily responsible for cryptococcosis, a fungal infection that occurs in about one million HIV/AIDS patients, causing over 600,000 deaths annually.
[src:yeast/yeast] The cells of these yeast are surrounded by a rigid polysaccharide capsule, which helps to prevent them from being recognised and engulfed by white blood cells in the human body.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts of the genus *Candida*, another group of opportunistic pathogens, cause oral and vaginal infections in humans, known as candidiasis.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Candida* is commonly found as a commensal yeast in the mucous membranes of humans and other warm-blooded animals.
[src:yeast/yeast] However, sometimes these same strains can become pathogenic.
[src:yeast/yeast] The yeast cells sprout a hyphal outgrowth, which locally penetrates the mucosal membrane, causing irritation and shedding of the tissues.
[src:yeast/yeast] *Candida glabrata* is the second most common *Candida* pathogen after *C. albicans*, causing infections of the urogenital tract, and of the bloodstream (candidemia).
[src:yeast/yeast] *C. auris* has been more recently identified.
[src:yeast/yeast] Some species of fungi live most of their life cycles as molds in soil, but upon entering a host animal, they transition to a yeast form, along with expression of virulence factors that convert them into effective and dangerous pathogens.
[src:yeast/yeast] These are known as dimorphic fungi and are typically capable of reproduction in the typical yeast fashion, including via budding.
[src:yeast/yeast] In these organisms, the yeast form transition is required for pathogenicity; if the transition is stopped somehow, the mold form does not cause disease.
[src:yeast/yeast] The rounded and separated forms of yeasts help them to spread through the bloodstream to organ systems.
[src:yeast/yeast] In some infections caused by dimorphic fungi, such as emergomycosis, respiratory symptoms are uncommon, even though the fungus initially enters through the lungs.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most molds are not dimorphic, and only a very small number of species cause dimorphic fungal disease in humans.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeasts are able to grow in foods with a low pH (5.0 or lower) and in the presence of sugars, organic acids, and other easily metabolized carbon sources.
[src:yeast/yeast] During their growth, yeasts metabolize some food components and produce metabolic end products.
[src:yeast/yeast] This causes the physical, chemical, and sensible properties of a food to change, and the food is spoiled.
[src:yeast/yeast] The growth of yeast within food products is often seen on their surfaces, as in cheeses or meats, or by the fermentation of sugars in beverages, such as juices, and semiliquid products, such as syrups and jams.
[src:yeast/yeast] The yeast of the genus *Zygosaccharomyces* have had a long history as spoilage yeasts within the food industry.
[src:yeast/yeast] This is mainly because these species can grow in the presence of high sucrose, ethanol, acetic acid, sorbic acid, benzoic acid, and sulfur dioxide concentrations, representing some of the commonly used food preservation methods.
[src:yeast/yeast] Methylene blue is used to test for the presence of live yeast cells.
[src:yeast/yeast] In oenology, the major spoilage yeast is *Brettanomyces bruxellensis*.
[src:yeast/yeast] An Indian study of seven bee species and nine plant species found 45 yeast species from 16 genera colonise the nectaries of flowers and honey stomachs of bees.
[src:yeast/yeast] Most were members of the genus *Candida*; the most common species in honey bee stomachs was *Dekkera intermedia*, while the most common species colonising flower nectaries was *Candida blankii*.
[src:yeast/yeast] Although the mechanism is not fully understood, it was found that *A. indica* flowers more if *Candida blankii* is present.
[src:yeast/yeast] In another example, *Spathaspora passalidarum*, found in the digestive tract of bess beetles, aids the digestion of plant cells by fermenting xylose.
[src:yeast/yeast] Many fruits produce different types of sugars that attract yeasts, which ferment the sugar and turns it into alcohol.
[src:yeast/yeast] Fruit eating mammals find the scent of alcohol attractive as it indicates a ripe, sugary fruit which provides more nutrition.
[src:yeast/yeast] In turn, the mammals helps disperse both the fruit's seeds and the yeast's spores.
[src:yeast/yeast] Yeast and small hive beetle have mutualistic relationship.
[src:yeast/yeast] While small hive beetle is attracted by the pheromone released by the host honeybee, yeast can produce a similar pheromone which have the same attractive effect to the small hive beetle.
[src:yeast/yeast] Therefore, yeast facilitates SHB's infestation if the beehive contains yeast inside.
